# A Tribute to Jahangir Kaka: The Man Behind the Screen

![Portrait of Gulam Mohiuddin / Dino Shafiq](https://i.ibb.co/Lz8SbPDb/IMG-5701.jpg)
*Gulam Mohiuddin, famously known as Dino Shafiq or Ali Nadim, but always remembered by us as our beloved Jahangir kaka.*

To the world, he was Dino Shafiq, the talented actor who brought smiles to millions. To fans of the beloved TV series *Mind Your Language*, he was the unforgettable Pakistani gentleman, Ali Nadim. But to me and our family, he was simply Gulam Mohiuddin—a beloved son, a cherished brother, and my dear uncle, Jahangir kaka.

This is a tribute to remember him not just for the characters he played, but for the man he truly was. 

### Family Roots and Heritage

In those days, our family did not use a western-style surname system. We were bound not by a shared last name, but by deep family ties. Jahangir kaka was a loving son to my grandparents, Hasena Banu and Gulam Merajuddin. 

He grew up surrounded by a large, bustling family. He was a brother to three brothers and four sisters:
*   **His Brothers:** My father, the late Muhammad Salahuddin (his elder brother), the late Moinuddin Ahmed, and Erfanuddin Ahmed.
*   **His Sisters:** The late Sufia Khatoon, the late Fatema Banu, the late Khaleda Banu, and his youngest sister, the late Abeda Banu.

Though Jahangir kaka never married and had no children of his own, his legacy was carried on through the stories shared by his siblings. I came to know the many vibrant chapters of his life mainly through my parents, who were closer in age to him and shared a wealth of precious memories.

### The Vibrant Youth and "Mr. East Pakistan"

From everything I have come to understand, Jahangir kaka was a restless, energetic young man with a spirit that wanted to conquer the world. He was handsome, driven, and had a deep passion for sports, music, and physical fitness. 

Alongside his education, he dedicated himself to bodybuilding. My father used to keep books and magazines featuring photographs of Jahangir kaka's bodybuilding poses, showcasing just how exceptionally good he was at it. His dedication to the sport led to a defining moment in his early life. 

In the late 1950s, he left Dhaka, East Pakistan, to participate in a major bodybuilding competition in Pakistan, most likely in Karachi. It was there that his hard work paid off, and he proudly won the title of **"Mr. East Pakistan."**

### A Connection Beyond Time

When I watch his movies or TV shows today, I do not just see an actor on a screen. I see his eyes, his nose, and the unique way he talks. Those familiar expressions instantly remind me of the stories my parents and grandmother shared. It gives me a profound sense of connection—a connection of blood, family heritage, and enduring love. 

He may have belonged to the world as Dino Shafiq, but in our hearts, he will always be our restless, vibrant, and deeply loved Jahangir kaka.


